Here is an example of a Discord bot using Discord.js v14 with a single slash command, `ban`:
```
const { Client, GatewayIntentBits } = require('discord.js');
const client = new Client({
  intents: [
    GatewayIntentBits.Guilds,
    GatewayIntentBits.GuildMembers,
    GatewayIntentBits.GuildMessages,
    GatewayIntentBits.GuildBans
  ]
});

client.commands = new Map();

client.commands.set('ban', {
  name: 'ban',
  description: 'Bans a user from the server',
  options: [
    {
      name: 'user',
      description: 'The user to ban',
      type: 'user',
      required: true
    }
  ],
  execute: async (interaction) => {
    const user = interaction.options.getUser('user');
    const member = interaction.guild.members.cache.get(user.id);
    if (!member) {
      return interaction.reply({ content: 'User not found', ephemeral: true });
    }
    await interaction.guild.bans.create(user, 7);
    interaction.reply({ content: `Banned ${user.tag} from the server`, ephemeral: true });
  }
});

client.on('ready', () => {
  console.log('Bot is online!');
});

client.on('interactionCreate', async (interaction) => {
  if (!interaction.isCommand()) return;
  const command = client.commands.get(interaction.commandName);
  if (!command) return;
  try {
    await command.execute(interaction);
  } catch (error) {
    console.error(error);
    interaction.reply({ content: 'There was an error while executing this command', ephemeral: true });
  }
});

client.login('YOUR_BOT_TOKEN');
```
Here's an explanation of the code:

* We create a new `Client` instance and set the `intents` to include `Guilds`, `GuildMembers`, `GuildMessages`, and `GuildBans`.
* We define a `Map` called `commands` to store our slash commands.
* We add a single command called `ban` with the following options:
	+ `name`: The name of the command.
	+ `description`: A brief description of the command.
	+ `options`: An array of options for the command. In this case, we have a single option called `user` that requires a `user` type.
	+ `execute`: The function that will be called when the command is invoked. This function takes an `interaction` object as an argument.
* We define an `execute` function for the `ban` command that:
	+ Gets the user mentioned in the command options.
	+ Checks if the user is a member of the guild. If not, returns an error message.
	+ Bans the user from the guild using `interaction.guild.bans.create()`.
	+ Sends a success message to the user.
* We define event listeners for `ready` and `interactionCreate`. The `ready` event is triggered when the bot is fully initialized, and the `interactionCreate` event is triggered when a slash command is invoked.
* In the `interactionCreate` event listener, we check if the interaction is a command and if the command exists. If it does, we call the `execute` function for the command. If there's an error, we log the error and send an error message to the user.
* Finally, we log in the bot using the `login` method and pass in our bot token.

Note that you'll need to replace `YOUR_BOT_TOKEN` with your actual bot token. You can obtain a bot token by creating a bot on the Discord Developer Portal and clicking on the "Token" button.

